VT5\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1WxDaxD5az6kdOjJncmGph37z0BPNhV1fNAH_g7IkpC0/htmlview|title=2018 House Popular Vote Tracker|last1=Wasserman|first1=David|last2=Flinn|first2=Ally|date=November 7, 2018|publisher=Cook Political Report|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Republican primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Declared=====\n* [[Larry Bucshon]], incumbent U.S. Representative<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.courierpress.com/story/news/2019/04/15/no-promises-after-2020-but-bucshon-game-one-more-race/3473835002/|title=No promises after 2020, but Bucshon is game for one more race|last1=Langhorne|first1=Thomas B.|date=April 15, 2019|newspaper=Evansville Courier & Press|accessdate=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Primary results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Republican primary results\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = [[Larry Bucshon]] (incumbent)\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Democratic primary===\n====Candidates====\n=====Declared=====\n*Ron Drake, attorney<ref name=\"IN08\">{{cite web |last1=Langhorne |first1=Thomas B. |title=Trio of Democrats face uphill charge against Bucshon |url=https://www.courierpress.com/story/news/2020/02/16/trio-democrat-candidates-face-uphill-charge-against-larry-bucshon/4760075002/ |website=Courier & Press |date=February 16, 2020}}</ref>\n*Thomasina Marsili, registered emergency medical technician<ref name=\"IN08\"/>\n*Mike Webster, computer distributions manager for [[SABIC]]<ref name=\"IN08\"/>\n\n=====Declined=====\n*[[John R. Gregg]], former [[speaker of the Indiana House of Representatives]] and nominee for [[Governor of Indiana]] in [[Indiana gubernatorial election, 2012|2012]] and [[Indiana gubernatorial election, 2016|2016]]<ref name=\"IN08\"/>\n*Jonathan Weinzapfel, former mayor of [[Evansville, Indiana|Evansville]]<ref name=\"IN08\"/>\n*Charlie Wyatt, mayor of [[Boonville, Indiana|Boonville]]<ref name=\"IN08\"/>\n\n====Primary results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Democratic primary results\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Ron Drake\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Thomasina Marsili\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate = Mike Webster\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===General election===\n====Results====\n{{Election box begin no change\n| title = Indiana's 8th congressional district, 2020\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = [[Larry Bucshon]] (incumbent)\n| party      = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes      = \n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = TBD\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes      = \n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = James D. Rodenberger\n| party      = Libertarian Party (United States)\n| votes      = \n| percentage =\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes      = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District 9==\n{{see also|Indiana's 9th congressional district}}\nThe 9th district is based in south central Indiana, and includes the cities of [[Bloomington, Indiana|Bloomington]] and [[Jeffersonville, Indiana|Jeffersonville]]. The incumbent is Republican [[Trey Hollingsworth]], who was re-elected with 56.5% of the vote in 2018.<ref name=\"HPVT\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1WxDaxD5az6kdOjJncmGph37z0BPNhV1fNAH_g7IkpC0/htmlvi