es)\n| votes      = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n| candidate  = TBA\n| party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes      = \n| percentage = \n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes      = \n| percentage = 100.0\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==District 5==\n{{see also|Indiana's 5th congressional district}}The 5th district encompasses northern [[Indianapolis]] and its eastern and northern suburbs, including [[Marion, Indiana|Marion]], [[Carmel, Indiana|Carmel]], [[Anderson, Indiana|Anderson]], [[Noblesville, Indiana|Noblesville]], [[Fishers, Indiana|Fishers]], and parts of [[Kokomo, Indiana|Kokomo]]. The incumbent is Republican [[Susan Brooks]], who was re-elected with 56.8% of the vote in 2018,<ref name=\"HPVT4\">{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1WxDaxD5az6kdOjJncmGph37z0BPNhV1fNAH_g7IkpC0/htmlview|title=2018 House Popular Vote Tracker|last1=Wasserman|first1=David|last2=Flinn|first2=Ally|date=November 7, 2018|publisher=Cook Political Report|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref> and announced on June 14, 2019 that she would not seek re-election to a 5th term in Congress.<ref name=\"Brooks2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/politics/elections/2019/06/14/susan-brooks-indiana-republican-congress-will-not-run-election-2020/1454213001/|title=Exclusive: Indiana Republican Susan Brooks will not seek re-election to Congress|last1=Groppe|first1=Maureen|date=June 14, 2019|newspaper=The Indianapolis Star|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Republican primary===\n=====Declared=====\n*Kent W. Abernathy, former commissioner of  Indiana's Bureau of Motor Vehicles<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erdody |first1=Lindsey |title=Former BMV commissioner running for Congress |url=https://www.ibj.com/articles/former-bmv-commissioner-running-for-congress |website=Indianapolis Business Journal |accessdate=October 8, 2019 |date=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n*Andrew Bales, retired teacher<ref>{{Cite web|titl