idates\n* [https://dorris2020.com/ D. Liam Dorris (D) for Congress]\n* [http://www.votefortrey.com/ Trey Hollingsworth (R) for Congress]\n* [https://tonyaforcongress.com/ Tonya Millis (L) for Congress]\n* [https://www.andyruff.org/ Andy Ruff (D) for Congress]\n\n{{2020 United States elections}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States House of Representatives elections|Indiana]]\n[[Category:United States House of Representatives elections in Indiana|2020]]\n[[Category:2020 Indiana elections|House]]\n{{Indiana-election-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tgmod", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeneral election:source added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_United_States_House_of_Representatives_elections_in_Indiana"}
{"title_page": "Willy Bo Richardson", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name = Willy Bo Richardson\n| image = File:Willy Bo Richardson Studio.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alt = Willy Bo Richardson\n| caption = Willy Bo Richardson\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|6|8|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = \n| field = Painting\n| training = [[University of Wisconsin]], [[UT Austin]], and [[Pratt Institute]]\n| movement =\n| works =\n| patrons =\n| awards =\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Willy Bo Richardson''' (born June 8, 1974) is an American artist from [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]. Richardson is regarded as one of many contemporary painters revisiting late Modernism.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dad why do you paint Stripes?|url = http://www.pyragraph.com/2016/11/dad-why-do-you-paint-stripes/|website = Pyragraph}}</ref>  Describing his paintings as \u201cphilosophy in motion,\u201d Richardson works solely within the framework of vertical strokes. He exhibits his paintings internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Soul of Santa Fe|url = http://issuu.com/willyrichardson/docs/destinasian/3?e=8101390/2242324|website = [[DestinAsian]]|access-date = 2016-01-14|page = 108}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = FROM DARKNESS: LIGHT|url = https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1609937651.html|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160316033331/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1609937651.html|url-status = dead|archive-date = March 16, 2016|website = Santa Fe Reporter (subscription required)|access-date = 2016-01-14|date = November 5, 2008|last = Fischer|first = Zane}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRichardson was born in [[Santa Fe, NM]]. His father was a master wood-worker, and his mother founded the first mediation center in the Southwest. He studied at [[UW Madison]] and received a BA from [[University of Texas at Austin]]. While at UT Austin, he counted [[Peter Saul]] among his teachers.\n\nLiving in Philadelphia in 1997, he was writing and painting. Richardson jokes, \"I wrote a really bad coming of age novel, and the next year I checked myself in to graduate school for painting at [[Pratt Institute]]\" in Brooklyn. He received an MFA there in 2000. He and his wife lived in New York City for a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Willy Bo Richardson: Artist Profile|url = https://santafeartstudio.com/profiles/willy-bo-richardson-artist-profile/|website = Santa Fe Art Studio}}</ref> He worked as a painting technician at [[Cooper Union]] from 2001-2007. \n\n==Career==\nRichardson was a faculty member at [[Santa Fe University of Art and Design]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Studio Arts Faculty|url = http://santafeuniversity.edu/academics/studio-arts/faculty/|website = Santa Fe University of Art and Design|access-date = 2016-01-14}}</ref> In 2011 his work was included in the exhibition at Jason McCoy Gallery in New York titled, \"70 Years of Abstract Painting \u2013 Excerpts\".  The show assembled works by a selection of modern and contemporary painters, including [[Josef Albers]], [[Hans Hofmann]] and [[Jackson Pollock]]. In 2012 he showed a body of work in the exhibition \"Watercolors\u201d\" at the Phillips de Pury headquarters in Chelsea New York.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Willy Bo Richardson - Watercolors - galleryIntell|url = http://www.galleryintell.com/willy-bo-richardson-watercolors/|website = galleryIntell|access-date = 2016-01-14|language = en-US|last = Nazarevskaia|first = Kristina}}</ref> In 2014 Richardson was selected to be one of the [[SITE Santa Fe]] SPREAD finalists. His work and vision was featured on the [[KNME-TV]] PBS weekly arts series \u00a1COLORES!.<ref>{{cite web|title=Willy Bo Richardson, The Impressionists, Regional Theater, Jack Ross|url=http://www.newmexicopbs.org/productions/colores/february-7-2014/|publisher=New Mexico PBS|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> Richardson's painting titled \"Number 1,\" 1999 was acquired by the [[Albuquerque Museum]] in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.unm.edu/news/tamarind-institute-presents-no-modifiers-an-exhibition|title=Tamarind Presents: No Modifiers. Featured works created by graduate students and professional guest artists|last=|first=|date=|website=The University of New Mexico|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. He was a guest artist at the [[Tamarind Institute]] at the University of New Mexico in 2019. Richardson is represented by [[Richard Levy Gallery]] in Albuquerque.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{officialwebsite|http://willyborichardson.com/}}\n* Wright, Margaret. [http://adobeairstream.com/art/painters-point-way-richard-levy-gallery/ Painters Point the Way at Richard Levy Gallery] Adobe Airstream, August\u2013September 2014 Edition.\n* LaSalle-Hopkins, Patti. [https://www.newmexico.org/nmmagazine/articles/post/on-the-line/ On the Line] New Mexico Magazine, April 2018 Edition.\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Willy Bo}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Abstract painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from Santa Fe, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Painters from New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Southwestern artists|New Mexico]]\n[[Category:People from New Mexico by occupation]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Mexico]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name = Willy Bo Richardson\n| image = File:Willy Bo Richardson Studio.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alt = Willy Bo Richardson\n| caption = Willy Bo Richardson\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|6|8|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = \n| field = Painting\n| training = [[University of Wisconsin]], [[UT Austin]], and [[Pratt Institute]]\n| movement =\n| works =\n| patrons =\n| awards =\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Willy Bo Richardson''' (born June 8, 1974) is an American artist. Richardson is regarded as one of many contemporary painters revisiting late Modernism.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dad why do you paint Stripes?|url = http://www.pyragraph.com/2016/11/dad-why-do-you-paint-stripes/|website = Pyragraph}}</ref>  Describing his paintings as \u201cphilosophy in motion,\u201d Richardson works solely within the framework of vertical strokes. He exhibits his paintings internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Soul of Santa Fe|url = http://issuu.com/willyrichardson/docs/destinasian/3?e=8101390/2242324|website = [[DestinAsian]]|access-date = 2016-01-14|page = 108}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = FROM DARKNESS: LIGHT|url = https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1609937651.html|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160316033331/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1609937651.html|url-status = dead|archive-date = March 16, 2016|website = Santa Fe Reporter (subscription required)|access-date = 2016-01-14|date = November 5, 2008|last = Fischer|first = Zane}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRichardson was born in [[Santa Fe, NM]]. His father was a master wood-worker, and his mother founded the first mediation center in the Southwest. He studied at [[UW Madison]] and received a BA from [[University of Texas at Austin]]. While at UT Austin, he counted [[Peter Saul]] among his teachers.\n\nLiving in Philadelphia in 1997, he was writing and painting. Richardson jokes, \"I wrote a really bad coming of age novel, and the next year I checked myself in to graduate school for painting at [[Pratt Institute]]\" in Brooklyn. He received an MFA there in 2000. He and his wife lived in New York City for a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Willy Bo Richardson: Artist Profile|url = https://santafeartstudio.com/profiles/willy-bo-richardson-artist-profile/|website = Santa Fe Art Studio}}</ref> He worked as a painting technician at [[Cooper Union]] from 2001-2007. \n\n==Career==\nRichardson was a faculty member at [[Santa Fe University of Art and Design]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Studio Arts Faculty|url = http://santafeuniversity.edu/academics/studio-arts/faculty/|website = Santa Fe University of Art and Design|access-date = 2016-01-14}}</ref> In 2011 his work was included in the exhibition at Jason McCoy Gallery in New York titled, \"70 Years of Abstract Painting \u2013 Excerpts\".  The show assembled works by a selection of modern and contemporary painters, including [[Josef Albers]], [[Hans Hofmann]] and [[Jackson Pollock]]. In 2012 he showed a body of work in the exhibition \"Watercolors\u201d\" at the Phillips de Pury headquarters in Chelsea New York.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Willy Bo Richardson - Watercolors - galleryIntell|url = http://www.galleryintell.com/willy-bo-richardson-watercolors/|website = galleryIntell|access-date = 2016-01-14|language = en-US|last = Nazarevskaia|first = Kristina}}</ref> In 2014 Richardson was selected to be one of the [[SITE Santa Fe]] SPREAD finalists. His work and vision was featured on the [[KNME-TV]] PBS weekly arts series \u00a1COLORES!.<ref>{{cite web|title=Willy Bo Richardson, The Impressionists, Regional Theater, Jack Ross|url=http://www.newmexicopbs.org/productions/colores/february-7-2014/|publisher=New Mexico PBS|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> Richardson's painting titled \"Number 1,\" 1999 was acquired by the [[Albuquerque Museum]] in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.unm.edu/news/tamarind-institute-presents-no-modifiers-an-exhibition|title=Tamarind Presents: No Modifiers. Featured works created by graduate students and professional guest artists|last=|first=|date=|website=The University of New Mexico|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. He was a guest artist at the [[Tamarind Institute]] at the University of New Mexico in 2019. Richardson is represented by [[Richard Levy Gallery]] in Albuquerque.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{officialwebsite|http://willyborichardson.com/}}\n* Wright, Margaret. [http://adobeairstream.com/art/painters-point-way-richard-levy-gallery/ Painters Point the Way at Richard Levy Gallery] Adobe Airstream, August\u2013September 2014 Edition.\n* LaSalle-Hopkins, Patti. [https://www.newmexico.org/nmmagazine/articles/post/on-the-line/ On the Line] New Mexico Magazine, April 2018 Edition.\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Willy Bo}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Abstract painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from Santa Fe, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Painters from New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Southwestern artists|New Mexico]]\n[[Category:People from New Mexico by occupation]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Mexico]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Badabara", "label": "safe", "comment": "added place of residence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willy_Bo_Richardson"}
